Ever since, he and the newly formed Withernsea Pier and Promenade Association - with the help of @Withsbiglocal and funding from @TNLUK - have been working against council resistance and Covid delays for a new pier. Along the way, they‚Äôve revamped the towers and the whole prom https://t.co/IGMpXAvf0R

By chance, steampunker Torkel Larsen - originally from Norway but with grandparents from Blackpool and ‚Äúpiers in the blood‚Äù- bought a house in Withernsea that originally belonged to a historian (and hoarder). Clearing it out, he found the original architects‚Äô drawings of the pier https://t.co/9TJmtTxjwV

Now all you can see of the old pier are the gateway towers, said to have been modelled on Conwy Castle in North Wales, guarding the town even as it faces coastal erosion, chronic deprivation and rising costs of living https://t.co/FNb1rmftfj

Withernsea was once a bustling seaside resort, with tourists coming from all over the country to enjoy the beaches, the seafood and the buzzing Victorian pier. But more than 100 years ago, a series of storms and shipwrecks knocked the pier into the crashing North Sea

RT @MatthewdAncona: Tinsel and champagne for the few‚Ä¶.but for others so very much less. Read this important piece on the hunger crisis by ‚Å¶‚Ä¶

Data released by the @Food_Foundation this week showed that food insecurity had risen nearly 1 per cent in the past month alone. Costs of living, inflation, fuel prices, supply issues, tax rises and cuts to benefits... what we do know is that the crisis is about to get worse

A landmark report from the @FoPHNproject in September 2021 outlines the crisis in UK public nutrition, and the terrible cost of austerity cuts, Brexit supply issues and pandemic losses:
https://t.co/mQQDWdlKYS

There's also a huge social benefit ‚Äì initiatives I visited in Cheltenham, Gloucester and York also functioned as weekly social clubs that people actually enjoyed going to. Clubs in @TangHBigLocal , @podsbiglocal and @BigLocalChelt that #reducefoodwaste also combat isolation
Alternatives also help to combat the excessive annual food waste in the UK, and communities take pride in helping the environment rather than feel shame in relying on "hand outs"

It's not to detract from the amazing efforts of food-bank networks and the volunteers who staff them, but there are many reasons why people are reluctant to use them. Lack of referral, shame, stigma, fear of intrusion... especially in small communities, these can all deter

We know that the crisis is worsening, thanks to data on food banks from @TrussellTrust and @foodnetwork. But we don't know the extent, because people are increasingly relying on alternatives like food clubs, waste redistribution and citizens' supermarkets, e.g. @Feeding_Britain

As journalist-at-large with @LocalTrust, I've been travelling to some of England's most deprived areas. In the first of my @Independent long read series, I report on the growing national food poverty crisis and the rise of food-bank alternatives https://t.co/WGlhMQf6SL

I‚Äôve lived outside London, so I know how great it can be, and I doubt if I‚Äôll stay here forever, but I‚Äôll be damned if I ever try and act like this world-class city was a shithole
The worst thing about these articles? They‚Äôre perfectly predictable. Oh you swapped a busy metropolis for the rural idyll and now you marvel at the slower place and dearth of amenities? Shocking

What I love most about London is that anyone can become a Londoner, if you can swing it financially. If you live here, and love it here, and open your mind to the city, you‚Äôre part of it. On par with people who were born here. How many other places can you say that about?

It‚Äôs also an almost overwhelmingly straight white British perspective. For so many - immigrants, LGBT people, non-English speakers, ethnic minorities, social outsiders - London represents unparalleled freedom. I‚Äôm proud to be from here

‚ÄúI left London and all I got was this faux sense of perspective on what is objectively one of the world‚Äôs top destinations‚Äù articles have hit saturation level. Let‚Äôs have some pieces from people who came to London and flourished

Living in London is very much not for everyone - obviously! It‚Äôs a huge, packed, pricey metropolis with dodgy weather and a joke of a housing market. But the sheer volume of content of people trying to convince themselves that London sucks because they chose to leave‚Ä¶ exhausting

The extent to which some people try to convince themselves (and their audiences) that London isn‚Äôt one of the most vibrant, welcoming cities in the world, just because *they* don‚Äôt want to live here, is astonishing.

Of course this has also coincided with the absolute gutting of subeditor teams, most of whom are still largely disproportionately focussed on print headlines anyway when a digital headline serves a totally different purpose and can often lead to much bigger danger for the author

In the print days you could at least hope to have your work read nearly to the end without a barrage of abuse. Now that that isn‚Äôt the case, social teams and digital subs / headline writers have a far bigger duty of care not to misrepresent the author‚Äôs words  - cynically or not

So either big publications hire specific digital beat roles, eg BBC‚Äôs misinformation reporter or Insider‚Äôs influencer reporters, or existing reporters, correspondents and editors really need to stop acting like it‚Äôs 2002 and the internet is just some irrelevant play den for kids.

Incel culture, and how it interacts with white supremacy, gun obsession and hardcore conspiracy theories online, is one of the most dangerous things happening online. And the salient point is it is not *just* happening online. This isn‚Äôt some noise in a chat room

For that matter, it *really* isn‚Äôt acceptable for reporters at national publications to be wilfully ignorant of all social media and how they work. Fair enough, you don‚Äôt want to use it, but you don‚Äôt want to be the person asking what Reddit is or how YouTube algorithm works

It just isn‚Äôt acceptable to have legacy crime correspondents, home affairs reporters and news editors treat the internet and all who dwell within like some murky newfangled nonsense. It‚Äôs 2021 and it‚Äôs a pretty key chunk of where culture - and radicalisation - happens

I‚Äôm not saying I‚Äôd do any better but some of the reporting on the Plymouth shooting has been atrocious. We‚Äôre saying once again: editors & reporters *need* to familiarise themselves with internet culture and incel movements. Or better yet, hire internet culture beat reporters
